    <h3>About</h3>
    <p>I live in Cambridge with my wife and two awesome dogs. I have been a technology enthusiast my entire life. From a young age I had two primary passions in life: technology and food. I grew up on a small farm in West Virginia, and partly due to my upbringing, I decided to pursue a career as a chef. I was very good at it. I held the position of Executive Chef at a number of highly regarded Boston establishments. During this time I was invited to cook at the prestigious <a href="http://www.jamesbeard.org " target="_blank">James Beard</a> House in NYC and was voted by my peers as one of Boston's <a href="http://stuffboston.com/2007/11/16/worth-their-salt-local-veteran-chefs-choose-their-favorite-young-guns#.U6TCXRbyDwI" target="_blank">“Top 5 Up and Coming Chefs”</a> by Boston’s Stuff Magazine. What I loved about the culinary arts is the need to continue learning and improving one’s skills, it also conditions a person to be both artistically creative and and strategically analytical. There are a few drawbacks to working as a chef however, so in the spring of 2014 I decided to start teaching myself web development. I fell in love, quit my job and enrolled in a Boston Ruby on Rails boot-camp called <a href="http://www.launchacademy.com/program" target="_blank">Launch Academy</a>. If you like, you can read my blog about <a href="http://nterrafranca.tumblr.com" target="_blank">my experience there.</a></p>
    <p>
      When I am not colaborating on a number of Rails projects I am cooking, experimenting with food and technology and brewing beer.
    </p>
